<div class="aos-AdaptiveWidth share aos-PLM">
<div class="aos-Article-ImageMain aos-MBM aos-FL aos-W100"><a data-fancybox="gallery" data-caption="Arnaud LagardÃ¨re" href="https://drsw10gc90t0z.cloudfront.net/AcuCustom/Sitename/DAM/529/ArnaudL.jpg"><img loading="lazy" src="https&#x3a;&#x2f;&#x2f;drsw10gc90t0z.cloudfront.net&#x2f;AcuCustom&#x2f;Sitename&#x2f;DAM&#x2f;529&#x2f;ArnaudL.jpg" alt="ArnaudL.jpg" title="ArnaudL.jpg" class="aos-Image aos-W100" />
<div class="aos-DS49-ImgCaption aos-MT5px aos-TAL"><span class="aos-NS aos-FWB">Arnaud LagardÃ¨re</span></div></a>
</div>
<div class="aos-MBS">
<div class="aos-DS49-WYSEdit"> <p>Arnaud LagardÃ¨re, chairman and c.e.o of the LagardÃ¨re group, which owns Hachette Livre, was indicted on Monday (29th April) for vote buying, abuse of power and dissemination of false or misleading information, the group confirmed in a statement released on Tuesday.Â </p>
<p>LagardÃ¨re, 63, has been banned from office temporarily, meaning that he is obliged to resign as the head of the group and Hachette Livre. LagardÃ¨re âfirmly disputesâ the charges and plans to appeal the decision.Â </p>
<p>According to the statement, the charges relate to events that took place in 2018 and 2019, and concern companies that LagardÃ¨re owns personally rather than group entities.</p>
<p>Conversely, a judicial source quoted by Agence France Presse (AFP) and reported by the French media suggests the indicment relates to the period between 2009 and 2022, when LagardÃ¨re used cash from two personal companies to finance his âlifestyle and personal expensesâ.Â </p>
<p>Later on Tuesday, the group announced that Jean-Christophe Thierry, chairman of the supervisory board of Vivendi pay TV subsidiary Canal+, would become temporary chairman and c.e.o. of the LagardÃ¨re group, and also of Hachette Livre, subject to approval by the latterâs board.Â </p>
<p>Vivendi, a French conglomerate controlled by the BollorÃ© family, bought the LagardÃ¨re group in November after a tussle over anti-trust issues. As part of the sale, Vivendi was obliged to sell off Editis, Franceâs second-largest publisher and closest rival to Hachette Livre.Â </p>
<p>According to AFP judicial source, the indictment follows an investigation which opened in April 2021.</p>
<p>This followed a complaint filed by the Amber Capital hedge fund, and alerts sent to financial regulator AutoritÃ© des Marches Financiers (AMF) and audit regulator Haut AutoritÃ© de lâAudit (H2H).</p>
<p>Following the 2003 death of group founder Jean-Luc LagardÃ¨re, his son and heir Arnaud is reported to have accumulated debts that forced him to sell the aerospace company EADS and several media outlets.</p> </div>
